\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. R. indica} (Willd.) Koehne, {\i Bot. Jahrb. }{\b 1}: 172 (1880). Stems 10-25 cm, erect from a creeping base, rather stout; branches few and short. Leaves mostly c. 10 × 3·5 mm, oblanceolate, obtuse, with a narrow, hyaline, cartilaginous margin. Flowers c. 2·5 mm, pinkish. Sepals 1-1·5 mm, triangular, acuminate; petals 0·5 mm, persistent; stamens 4. Style 1·5 mm; capsule 2·5 mm, globose, 4-valved.{\i  Rice-fields. N. Italy, C. Portugal}. [It Lu.] ({\i S. & E. Asia.})
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 The European plant is var.{\i  uliginosa} (Miq.) Koehne, apparently introduced from Japan. Var.{\i  indica} has a narrower hypanthium and is more freely branched.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. R. filiformis} (Bellardi) Hiern in Oliver,{\i  Fl. Trop. Afr.}{\b  2}: 468 (1871). Like {\b 1} but stems up to 35 cm and more delicate; leaves 2-5 mm, ovate-subcordate (the lowest sometimes linear-oblong), without hyaline margin, much shorter than internodes except near apex of stem; flowers 1·5-2 mm; sepals deltate, not acuminate; petals absent; stamens 2; style 0·5 mm; capsule ellipsoid.{\i  Rice-fields. N. Italy.} [It.] ({\i C. & S. Africa}.)
\par

